messages.content: All of you wake up the next morning when L and 64 barge into the room. The old man is brewing some tea.
Wow, that felt like no time passing at all. Insane. And why did nobody wake me up??
Inconsiderate sand people. I quickly head outside to try and make it back to the door in a rush.
L is the only one outside. "Jeez. Not a morning person, huh?" ((Roll perception))
You make the relatively obvious observation that he also looks like he just woke up.
"I don't know if I am, since apparently nobody deigned to alert me to it being morning. Maybe next time!" I continue speedwalking off.
((Which door?))
((growth))
They barge into the cabin. The Old Man is brewing some tea. 56, 57, and 63 are laying around the cabin and awoken by their entrance.
Snooooore... mimimimimimi... Snoooore..... mimimimimi...
https://tenor.com/view/good-night-cat-lizz-lizzy-gif-11840230538475982227
“Hm?” I arise.
I slam the door to the cabin open and start clapping my hands repeatedly. "Hey! It's morning! Let's go!"
I immediately sit up straight, reaching for my daggers. "WHO WANTS ME DEAD? I'LL KILL THE- Oh, it's just you, Fours." I stop reaching for my daggers.
"Bleagh..."
Do I still feel like shit?

"Ah, hello Leonie!" The old man holds out a cup of tea. "Tea, anyone?"

"Pass." L grabs a hold of the door's handle. 

"You have reached the door of growth. The blooming flower of your life into what it should have been. You are not tainted by any other door yet today.  Your requirement to open this door, Inmate #058, is to enter with Inmate #061 at the same time." The door speaks.
“Which one of us is 58, again…?” I yawn. “Also they can talk. That’s dumb.”
"Fifty-eight is L. And Sixty-one... hm..." I think a bit.
"Me." L. "61's supposed to be dead though. Is this game rigged?"
"Tea anyone?" The old man repeats. "Oh, and in case you've all forgotten... I was the illustrious number 17. I've never met whoever this 61 is."

"Oh. Yes. Oh my. Well, we already knew it was rigged. But it should be possible to open to make it possible to escape. So, either the goddess is a bigger b*tch than we thought, or someone lied about their number."
I hate numbers.
I poke 56. "You're not dead. Isn't that a delight?" I say that sounding as genuine as I can.
"I believe Marceline said she needed me for that door when she checked it yesterday, hmmmm." The old man drinks his own tea in an overperformed pitiful expression.
"Alright, so I've struck out on this door. I'll check the labyrinth, I guess. Who wants to try opening this one next?" L looks around.
"Me." I go to the handle.
Fuck, I forgot about the stupid requirements. "Look, I doubt anybody is lying about their numbers. Is it possible that the door is lying? I trust doors a lot less than I trust my fellow inmates."
"Ngh... Hooray."

"You have reached the door of growth. The blooming flower of your life into what it should have been. You are not tainted by any other door yet today.  Your requirement to open this door, Inmate #057, is to enter with Inmate #060 at the same time." The door. 

"That's the wolf. At least that one should be possible." L.
Oh, yeah, the requirement would be different for every person. Duh. God, I'm moving slowly today.
"I see. I'll go find John, then. Sixer, get up, we've gotta go." I start getting ready to leave.
I slide my way past Jon and grab at the handle.
"Who's my requirement?"
"I don't know. Grab the door and see."

"You have reached the door of growth. The blooming flower of your life into what it should have been. You are not tainted by any other door yet today.  Your requirement to open this door, Inmate #064, is to enter with Inmate #063 at the same time." Door.
I try to touch the door, I guess?
Who was that again...? Oh, yeah... Silvestris. Right. Okay. I think about grabbing her by the wrist and dragging her to the door, but I really need to get over myself a bit here.
I glance to her. "Hey... Silvestris. Do you... how are you doing? Did you sleep well?"

"You have reached the door of growth. The blooming flower of your life into what it should have been. You are not tainted by any other door yet today.  Your requirement to open this door, Inmate #056, is to enter while no one else on this island is inside. This is your isolation." Door.
“I’m fine. We doing this one? It’s right here, I guess.” Better than dealing with the village.
"Haaah?" I say, frowning. "So what, I'm just supposed to be alone? 'S that it???"
Oh, I see. "If you decide to go in alone, Sixer, I'll just find something else to do while you're there." I begin a routine of stretching to be ready for the day.
"Yeah, I mean, if you're feeling up for it."
"...is it okay if I call you Silver, by the way?"
"Or Sylvia?"
"Does the door lock behind 56 or does that just mean she should go in first?" L. The door obviously fails to answer this question.
"The only way to learn is by doing."
John enters the building.
"...Oh, hello!" I wave at it, propping myself off the ground a little.
It gives a bark in response. ((Roll animal handling))

This wolf does not seem to have much experience with unfamiliar wolves and the smaller than usual size of the pack tells you they definitely wouldn't want to risk fights against other wolves when they're clearly in some amount of danger. In short, its clearly welcoming you into the pack. You can't understand it specifically because it does not say words but it conveys a certain degree of welcomeness for John.

Aw, well, that's pretty cool! I don't know how to tell it that I already sort of have a pack without just talking at it, which I'm not sure it'd understand. Should I pet it? I don't want to pet it. That seems foolish. An unnecessary unbalancing of the power dynamic there. All that said, though, I really should be getting back to the door, to meet up with the others.

I get to my feet, carefully. And... nod at the elder wolf in acknowledgment, I suppose.
It howls into the air, waking up the rest of the pack. They all move behind the elder and give a slight bow of their head behind her.

Neat!

I wave them goodbye before leaving in direction of the old man's hut-slash-door. Or would they want to follow me? I guess we'll see!
They growl expectantly. Your grasp of their sort of language tells you they probably expect you to return their respect first.
Oh, um... I bow too? I thought I already bowed a little. Am I mucking this up?
The elder wolf gives slight bark and one of her followers begins digging into the ground. It pulls out pieces of raw meat with its mouth and presents them for John to take.

Do they... bury their meat? That doesn't seem very sanitary.

"Thank you!" I take it graciously. "I'll eat this later, alright?"

They have no idea what your words mean but they look back at their leader in confusion about John... Holding it with his paws? Truly absurd. The leader attempts to recreate John's posture and falls over.
"Oh! Are you alright?" I kneel by the elder.
She gets back up and licks your face generously. It would seem they are impressed by your unusual abilities for a wolf.
Wow! How wet. I think this is good. I let this happen for a bit before standing up straight again.
They disperse from their positions and begin digging up their own food. They seem satisfied with this welcoming ritual.

That went well!

"Goodbye, wolf friends!" I wave again. Okay, for real this time. There are doors to open. What if everyone's worried about me?
They wave their tails at you. That seems like the closest they can manage.

They tried their best!

I go. To the door.
Every inmate John met in the labyrinth is here, except 59. The old man is drinking tea and failing to offer it to anyone.
"Hello!" I am carrying some raw meat, if that wasn't clear.
I look at John. "Oh, fortuitous. John, the door asked for you so we could both enter. Let's go in."
“It just means at worst she has to go a different day.”
"Oh, is that so? Have you had breakfast yet?"

"If 56 goes in first and you're locked out, that means you need to find a different door today. I've got no clue how we're supposed to find the labyrinth and the birth involves a fight I'm not willing to take yet. Kind of a big risk to your efficiency. I say you take it. It'll tell us how these conditions work better and you can all just join me in finding more doors." L shrugs.
"I'm not hungry yet. I'll live if I go in first."
I jolt up. "I-I'll eat breakfast! And avoid the door. Yeah."
"Come on... You guys really don't want to experiment? We know she can't go in once you guys do. Why not send her in first?" L is smirking.

"Oh, alright." I shrug. "Does anyone want to cook and clean this meat while we're gone, maybe? I found some wolf friends when I woke up, and they dug this out of the ground for me. It doesn't seem sanitary, but I also have no other ideas for breakfast, really."
"You're just trying to piss me off!" I yell at him.
"Are you just scared of learning what your history looks like? Maybe you're not so different from the others?" L.

"Oh... That seems rather unhealthy. But I suppose there's no such thing as a free meal, hm?" The old man casually grabs a stick and hits it against the door like a match, causing it to light on fire. "I'll go make a cooking fire outside."

Do I know how to cook? I'm sure I can get *something* ready, at least. Plus, everyone will follow someone who cooks. 

"Alright, John. First, we need to wash that meat and then we can start cooking. Sixer, you go in the door for the experiment. Silvestris and Fours, you two start looking for more doors."
"Oh, what? Are we experimenting?"
"Wait, no, I don't even understand the point of this. Silvestris, can we just go in?"
"Why do I have to go first... I don't want to...!"
"It's fine if you don't want a nickname, also. Sorry if the suggestion was rude."
"The sooner you do this, the less you have to dread doing it ."
"Because you're a weak coward if you don't go. Do we need to kill you so you don't go dragging us down?" L says this in a completely casual tone.
"That seems unnecessary..."
I ~~break L’s kneecaps~~ slap him in the face.
"I'm not a weak coward!!!!!! You're a dipshit who should be set on fire!!!!"
Haha, yeah!
“The nickname was fine, incidentally.”
((Roll to hit for an unarmed strike))
I raise my eyebrow slightly, but approve.
He deserved that.
"Alright. Sylvia it is."
We can't be resorting to violence already, can we...?
"..." I shake my head. You don't get people to do things by insulting them. You let them believe they want to do it themselves.
That hits. ((What’s the damage.))
((his ego))
((3. This involves no dice.(?)))

"Ow." L rubs the bruise with an annoyed expression. "I obviously wasn’t going to do it. It’s like you guys have never even *heard* of manipulation." He groans and heads to the door. "Whatever. I’ve got nothing left here if you’re not gonna do the fun thing."
I stare at my hand and grumble.
L leaves, assuming no one tries to stop him.
“…Let’s just go, Fours.”
"Yeah. I agree."
"Thank you for doing what we all wanted to, by the way."
"Um, okay. Bye, guys."
I clear my throat. "Bye."
"Good luck."
"And.. thanks."
"Good luck to you two."
We go, presumably. To the door.
The growth one.
The door repeats its message for both, confirming they only need each other. Then it opens.
I pat her on the shoulder, then walk in.
I enter.

You are somewhere between child and teenager. A pre-teen, someone might say. You are sitting in the back of a carriage with a government employee escorting you. You only met her recently, when your father passed away. You don’t really want to think about that anymore though. The law dictates you had your few days of grieving supervised by the agent here and now it’s your time to find your new home. Needless to say, this isn’t an exciting concept.
“…So where is it?”

"Hm?" She turns from the window she was looking out of to look back at you. "Did you need something, dear?" Her tone is insufferably sweet as usual. At least you won’t need to see her anymore after today.
I sigh. “Nothing. It doesn’t matter.”

"Don’t worry, dear. *Maudoise* Orphanage promises the best orphan care in the whole city." The city, of course being a whole nation. She pronounces the word Maudoise with difficulty, which makes sense seeing as it’s a foreign word operating on a language system completely different than the local one.
“Hmph. I doubt those are very high standards.”
"Well…" She cringes. "The council promises a great life for all of its citizens. You’ll have a great time there!" The carriage pulls to a stop, allowing her to let out a sigh of relief.
I grab my things and leave the vehicle.

The Maudoise Orphanage is a relatively large building, but clearly not the richest you’ve seen. It’s about as much of a dump as you probably expected. Its name is written on a sign in front.

The government agent exits the vehicle and grabs your hand, leading you into the orphanage with a little too much force.
I whine vaguely.

They arrive in the entrance. An older white man you would one day know as #17 enters the room with a pleased expression. This is your first experience with someone from outside the city but you at least aware enough to know they just look like that. "Welcome, Yazmine." He nods politely. It goes without saying that he got your first name correctly.
I wave. Not sure how to approach this.

The agent walks out, satisfied. Good riddance, probably. 

"Come in, allow me to introduce you to your new brothers and sisters." The old man walks into a large playroom filled with various other orphans.
One of them, a younger version of inmate 64 who seems around your age, approaches you.

You are somewhere between child and teenager. A pre-teen, someone might say. You are sitting in the playing room of the orphanage, surrounded by various other 'kids' who they continue to refuse to accept as a family. In the corner, watching all of you, is the patron: An older man who your future self will call Inmate #017. For now though, you’ve been instructed to refer to him as father since you were a young child. He creeps you out more than you’d like from a father, though. The patron is the only person you’ve ever met with white skin, but you’re knowledgeable enough to know this just means he comes from something called Athelates.
What are the other kids doing?

Playing. Two of the older kids, around 16yo, are cooking lunch for everyone. The 4 kids younger than you, around 5 to 7yo, are playing some kind of incoherent game they invented that usually seems to just involve making up and then forgetting rules. The rest of the older kids are playing some kind of architectural game played by using sticks to form buildings. None of the kids are your age, age. There aren’t a lot of orphans in such a small nation and these big batches usually come from rare conflicts or natural disasters. The older kids lost their parents in a shipwreck, for example, while the younger ones apparently lost their parents in a mine collapse caused by an earthquake. No big events marked your parents’ deaths, though you’d rather not focus on that topic more. You just have to suck it up and hang out with people out of your age group.

I wouldn't really call these losers part of my 'age group', honestly. At least, not mentally. It's actually making me kind of sad to even have to watch these empty heads try to act out their little fantasies.
I walk over to one of the architectural projects and 'accidentally' knock loose a structural component with my shoe.
"Oops! Sorry, guys. My bad." I smirk.

"Hey, come on Roshan. That’s not cool." One of them replies with an exaggerated air of maturity, as though they’re desperate for you to respect them. And of course, Roshan is your first name. That’s an obvious fact.
"As if you'd have any idea what's cool or not."
I plop down next to them. "So, whatchya making?"
I inspect the little construct.
"It’s the council building. It’s way too old for the home of the government." You aren’t exactly a political scholar, but you know enough to know the ‘council’, whoever they are, runs the country.
"Yeah, I get what you mean. All these old people obsessed with their old shit."
I poke it with my finger.
"Hey, do you know what would be really awesome? If you made, like, a SUPER tall building. How tall do you think a building can get, even? Have people figured that out yet?"
"I bet you would have to make the bottom really wide, and have it thin out as it gets closer to the top..."
"That’s like a lot of materials though. And you’d need so many of the materials to be wasted on stairs."
"Hey, if some guy using my tower is too much of a pussy to use a ladder, that's on them, not me."
"And who even said you had to let people in? You've got no... artistic sense, or something."
I sigh loudly.
"Whatever. Have fun with your new world order. Make sure to reserve me a seat in there."
I slump onto my elbows.

"Ah, I’m so glad you’re all getting along despite your age differences. This family is truly blessed." The patron speaks up from right behind you, making you jump in shock at him suddenly being right there. He makes a few happy tears and wipes them with his beard.
The way that father can seem to cry on command still freaks me the fuck out. It is not that amazing, man.
"Y-yeah. It's cool. Thanks for keeping me around, and all."
I smile at him as convincingly as I can.

The sound of the front door opening is heard. That’s odd. Last you checked, none of the kids were out.

The patron smiles and heads towards the entrance.
I fall onto my back and peer upside-down at what's going on by the door.
It seems like… There’s a new kid arriving? A girl around your age.
Woah. Cool. I roll over quickly and push myself to my feet.
I wonder what insane thing happened to her to end up here. I doubt anyone's beating the shipwreck story, but you never know.
I walk over to her and reach out my hand. "Sup."
All about establishing yourself, really.
The new girl is a younger version of inmate 63.
"Ah, perfect. You 2 are already meeting." The old man smiles, motioning for the other kids to approach.
I survey the room, uncomfortable.
Not even gonna shake my hand? Huh.
I lower it. "So, what are you in for?"
“Hah.” Funny.

The other kids approach. Some are in their late teens while others are around 5yo. None of them except 64 are around the same age as 63.

"Everyone, this is your new sister. Yazmine Ali. Everyone say hi, Yazmine.”

"Hi, Yazmine." The kids awkwardly respond.
I get a buzz of happiness from my joke landing.
Would've preferred the handshake, though.
"Hiya, Yaz."
“…Hey.” I mumble. I don’t like all this. It’s suffocating. Couldn’t they have let me acclimate in my own way?

"This is Roshan Ghahremani." He points to 64 and then begins listing the names of the other children in order of proximity. None of them are relevant. Yazmine has a vague recollection of remembering hearing the last name Ghahremani somewhere before.

“Mmhm.” I consider following up on that familiarity, but it would probably be rude, especially here. I just… try to pay attention, I guess. Social clout among youth tends to be a simple matter of recognition and appearances.

"So, like, seriously, what's your story? That's kind of a... thing we do. It's the first question here everyone wants an answer to, so it's better to just get it out of the way now instead of being hounded about it for a month. Trust me on that one." I beckon the other kids in to hear what she has to say.

"And last but not least, we have me. I am Douglas Maudoise, a humble traveller from the Ardelunian Empire." Neither of you know what an ‘Ardelunian’ is. "But to you and all your new family… You can call me father." He smiles.
"Yeah, that's true. Now, come on. Out with it."
((Would Yazmine answer?))

My *story*? What exactly is he looking for?
“My dad is dead. I’m not.”

"Is that what you were asking, Roshan? What a cruel question... Yazmine must still be deep in grief. It's not right to drag this out of them." Douglas shakes his head in disappointment. 

The other kids who were definitely also interested pretend to agree and turn on Roshan.
“He shot straight. Don’t fault him for something I chose to say.” I grunt.
"Fair enough, I suppose. Please come in. Lunch is about to be served." Douglas walks away, causing the kids on food duty to go continue that.

I look down and kick the ground uncomfortably, making sure that father is out of earshot before speaking. "Um, I'm not a boy? Don't know what gave you that impression. Haha. You're right that it's not my fault, though."
I turn around and start walking towards the food.
Some of the younger kids snicker mockingly at Roshan.
Losers.
I don’t know what’s up with that. I get food as well.

They're served food. For whatever reason, this memory of food actually provides them the nutrients in the present. A nice convenience for once.

Douglas closes his eyes and adopts a prayer stance, which the kids follow. "Goddess Ismalisa... We hold this feast in your name and thank you for the great blessings you have brought upon this family. May you send the poor victims of those you enact justice upon here so that we may cleanse them in your name." The kids don't repeat the prayer, they just maintain the pose.
I breathe sharply in annoyance, but don’t say anything.
"So stupid." I mumble, softly enough that only Yaz can hear.
I smile.
"Now... Shall we eat?" He opens his eyes and smiles. The children do as instructed.
I eat. Food is one of the top five good things about living, honestly.
I chow the FUCK down.

They eat. Nothing particularly noteworthy occurs after this until its time to sleep. Yazmine and Roshan are left together for a while. As the older kids get themselves ready for bed and Douglas tends to the younger kids first.

“…What next?” I ask quietly. “Years of this, sure, but then… I dunno. You seem like a bookish kind of guy…rl. How often do little urchins like these buggers grow into anything but larger urchins? Realistically?”
I scoff. "I'm not a nerd. And hey, what's wrong with a big urchin?"
"I don't know what happens to people after they leave. I don't really care. If they want to roll around being all spiny, good for them. You know?"
"What you should be thinking about is what you want to do, not what's realistic. That's my advice."

I point out some of the architects from earlier. "If you think you might like building things, they're your guys." Then some of the younger kids. "Or you could just mess around with them for a bit while you work things out. Most of the people here are tolerable enough, even if you're not gonna get any deep insights from them."

I chuckle  - a little too loudly at first, before remembering people are sleeping and controlling my volume. “Not what’s realistic? What a thing to say. I seriously can’t get a read on you… well, what about you? What do you want, Roshan?”
"Well..."
I think about it for a second.

"I guess maybe it'd be cool to be a construction guy. Not the one desigining the fancy buildings, maybe, but the one doing the actual hard work and putting 'em together. What do you think about that?"
“You? A construction worker?” I look them over. “…I guess there’s time to figure all this out.”
"Hey, what's that supposed to mean?" I punch her softly on the shoulder and giggle, then get embarrassed at ever doing what could be described as a 'giggle' and stop.
But I'm still smiling.
"Look, I think you should get to bed. You look beat."
"You've got basically forever to think about this complicated stuff, right? You can figure it out."
"Even if I don't."

“…Right.” I think about countering the odd self-deprecation, but don’t. I don’t really know her.

I lie down in my bed or whatever it is here.
I lay down in mine, too.
I guess nothing's really changed. It's good to have something like this happen once in a while. Shake up the social balance. Keep things interesting. But she'll do fine. And I'll keep being fine.
And that's how the rest of their childhood together went. Sort of. ((Channel split))

It's been a few months since you met Yazmine. You can't deny that you care for her, perhaps even as your only real family, but family can also be difficult sometimes. Especially with Douglas around. God, you hate Douglas so much. You're running around the city with tears in your eyes. You can't even remember exactly what the argument was that led you to run out but all you remember is a sense of betrayal. Maybe Yazmine chose Douglas's side over yours. Maybe something completely different. It's been drowned out by nothing but raw teenage emotion. Eventually you have to stop to catch your breath. You're on some kind of bridge.

Fuck! Fuck! It's all so stupid, they're all so fucking stupid! They don't ever think about how I feel. It's always about them, always, always, they don't even try to care, they don't even try to pretend. Because who gives a shit, right? Who cares as long as they get to feel like they're right?
I lean against the bridge's rail, suddenly feeling like I'm going to vomit. The nausea just makes me more upset, like even my body is on their side. Like it knows that I'm some weak fucking moron.
Stupid, stupid, stupid.
I need to sit down. I lower myself to the ground, curling up into some sort of ball. The tears keep falling onto my knees.

I hate them. I hate them so, so much. I would kill them if I ever got the chance. The next time I see them, I'm going to do it. The closest thing I see, I'll grab it, I'll bash them until they have to admit that I'm not weak. I'm not nothing.
As soon as I have the thought, I know it's wrong. I know I... I would never do that. I would never think about it. It's-
I fall forward to my hands, and throw up onto the ground. Even after it's done, I keep retching for what feels like forever.
As soon as I can breathe again, the breath goes towards more sobs. I'm nothing. I lay on my side, as nothing.

"Oh my god! Are you okay!?" You hear an unfamiliar voice behind you. Well, it was unfamiliar then. You're certainly familiar with it now. The one you will someday know as Inmate 34 rushes towards you with a cloth. He's around your age.

My cheeks start burning with shame, that another person is seeing me like this. Everyone is going to know that this is what I'm really like. I can't keep it a secret anymore. It's done. But the sobs keep coming over me, so all I can do is pretend like he isn't there.
I know he's not going to go away, but I couldn't form a sentence even if I wanted to.
Just leave me alone... please...

He holds out the cloth towards you, offering it. He concentrates and with some amount of difficulty on his part you feel the nauseous feeling in your chest start to dissipate. This doesn't cure your sadness of course, but he's trying. "I'm here for you, okay? Cry as much as you need to."
I grab the cloth, weakly.
The snot covering my face soaks through it pretty much instantly, which doesn't do much to make me less disgusting.
I guess it was nice, though. I spit a few times to get the taste of puke out of my mouth.
"Do you need any help? My mother… Works nearby. I can get her to help."
I try to catch my breath. "N-n-no! I don't n-need your mommy... to help me! I just... I just..."
I start sobbing again. It's pointless.
He gives you a warm hug.
I jerk back, freaked out by the sudden contact. My snot and drool is clearly getting all over him. I know I'm fucking disgusting. But after a few seconds, I give in. The warmth... is good.
Between sobs, I ask. "Why... why do they always hate me?"
He's silent for a while. "I don't know. It's like the most hateful people are always the ones who most deserve to be hated. I guess our goddess has a cruel sense of humor."
A few moments later, I return the hug, pulling myself closer to him.
"I-I'm sorry..."

"Don't be. It sounds like no one deserved those tears more than you." 

((End session its late))
I tilt my face up at the man, not trying to stop the tears anymore. Somehow, though, not trying is more successful than trying ever was.
"Who... a-are you?"
I hiccup.
"...Daryush. What about you?"
"I'm... well..." I have an instinctual urge to look back down again, but resist it. "Y-you can call me whatever you want. It doesn't matter."
"It matters to me."

I think about it for a second. All the times they called me it, all the times it seemed like there was nothing coming out of their mouths but screams and showers of Roshan, Roshan. I don't know if I even own it anymore. But... they can have it.
"I'm Ghahremani."
"…Oh. I’m sorry." He seems… Guilty? You don’t like the first possibility that comes to mind for why. Not that this boy fits the profile, anyway.
I don't know what he's sorry for. I don't know what he's guilty for. But... weirdly, the fact that I'm not the only one here who has doubts about things makes me feel warmer.
"It's okay, Daryush."
"Can we... go somewhere?"
"Yeah." He holds out his hand for you to take.
I grab it tightly.
He helps you stand up.
"Where were you going before? I can just... follow."
"I don't want to slow down your day any more than I did already..."
"Just… Walking around aimlessly, really. I don’t actually like being home much."
"How come?"
"Just… You know. Annoying family type stuff."
"Yeah... yeah. I can't relate."
"But I hope you can... work it out."
"I guess we can walk around aimlessly, then. If you want."
"I guess we can."
I follow him around. Aimlessly.
Isn't it nice?

You spend time together. A long time, in fact. Daryush is important to you. He’s someone you return to as your source of freedom for a long time. That’s not something you can ever really find it within yourself to communicate to him though. You’re sure he doesn’t care that much about you, even if that doesn’t stop your attachment to him. He’ll never lead you astray…
